{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_chinooksalmon_ver03/data/sn84020662/00414185940/1948083001/0324.xml":{"full_text":"THE NOME NUGGET\nPublished Monday, Wednesday and Friday by The\nNOME PUBLISHING CO.\nNome, Alaska\nTelephone: Main 125 P. O. Box 618\nS1.50 PER MONTH S16.00 A YEAR\nEntered as second class matter October 14, 1943, at the postoffice\nat Nome, Alaska, under the Act of March 3, 1879.\n(Monday, August, 30, 1948)\nTOLERANCE IS STRENGTH\n(THE DENVER POST)\nThe strength of democracy was aptly illustrated last\nweek when the French chamber of deputies voted Pre\nmier Marie\u2019s government emergency powers to deal\nwith the national economic situation. That vote lifted a!\ngreat obstacle to the success of the European recovery\nplan. It is only the most recent in a series of incidents\nwhen men of greatly varying political beliefs gathered j\nthemselves to vote together\u2014and staved off the strong\nCommunist group in the French parliament.\nMany of the men who voted to give Finance Minister\nReynaud almost dictatorial economic powers did not\nwant to. The Socialists, in particular, fretted about giv\ning so much strength to the government. Yet they voted\nfor the bill because they knew that it was essential to\nthe success of the Marshall plan.\nBut, Tike other Communist parties, the French com\nmunists have always followed a strictly Kremlin line.\nNow they are attempting to pull France out of the ERP.\nIn 1939-40 they tried to keep her out of the war against\nGermany\u2014after signature of the Berlin-Moscow pact.1\nIf there is any doubt as to the ultimate loyalty of\nother Communist parties, there should be none as to the\nloyalty of the French communists. To the detriment of\nFrance they have consistently looked to the east. Dur\ning the war, Maurice Thorez, secretary of the party, de\nserted from the French army rather than fight against\nStalin\u2019s temporary allies.\nAfter the war, Uhe Communists first tried to gain con\ntrol of the government. Failing that, they did take over\nthe ministry of industry. They were so much more con\ncerned with proselyting than production that the Com\nmunist minsiter of industry was finally removed. Last\nwinter, they attempted to stage a general strike to de\nfeat the Marshall plan, cause chaos in France and gain\ncontrol of the government. They supported the inter\nests of France only between 1941 and 1945, when\nFrench interests were the same as those of Moscow\u2014to\ndefeat the Nazis.\nPerhaps it is difficult to understand why the French\ndemocracy tolerates a party which has so openly shown\nits derision of freedom and its foreign loyalty. Not to the\nFrench. With the exception of General de Gaulle and\nthe extreme ^ight, they believe that every man should\nbe entitled to his opinions, and they know it would be\ndangerous to force the Communists underground.\nBeing intensely practical, as well as intensely demo\ncratic, the French tolerate their Communists.\nOf course this has made for trouble. Yet it has not\nmade nearly so much trouble as the presence of strong\ndemocratic elements would make in a Communist po\nlice state\u2014if they were ever permitted. The commun\nists do not permit freedoms or democratic parties to ex\nist, because they know that those would be their down\nfall. Democracy can despise Communism but tolerates\nCommunists. No brand of totalitarianism can tolerate\ndemocracy, for that toleration would destroy them.\nThere is the strength of democracy.\n1\nRETREAT IN EUROPE\n(By Dorothy Thompson)\nAlthough the latest headlines proclaim \u201cMoscow\nProspects Brighter\u201d they are entirely misleading, if by\n\u201cbrighter\u201d is meant more favorable to the west. These\nnegotiations will produce nothing unless a further con\ncession to Russia. Meanwhile their continuation is, in\nitself, a concession.\nFor at the outset we took the view that the blockade\nof Berlin must be lifted before \u201cformal high level four\nCONFERENCE W A BOLER FACTORY\npower consultations\u201d could begin. Whatever \u2018formal\u201d\nand \u201chigh level\u201d may mean, western diplomatic agents\nhave been consulting in Moscow with both Stalin and\nMolotov while the blockade is not lifted but tightened.\nThe resulting half truce is being used by the Russians\nto strengthen their economic positions in the city and\nreach toward new objectives.\nNot words but acts are decisive in this world. While\nwe negotiate in Moscow, there also has been aDanubian\nconference in which Western Europe and the United\nStates have been decisively defeated. The control of the\nmost important river highway of southern Europe has\npassed entirely into the hands of Russia and her satel\nlite states. The Danube is a German and Austrian river\nas well as Hungarian, Czechoslovak and Romanian\nstream, rising as it does in the German Black Forest and\nemptying into the Black Sea. Its importance to all Eu\nrope is such that the treaty of Versailles put it under an\ninternational commission, and its importance to Ger\nmany such that two representatives of German states\nwere put on the commission.\nWhat the \u201cblue Danube\u201d means to Austria is cele\nbrated in folklore, painting, economic statistics and the\nworld\u2019s most famous wraltz, but a \u201cfree and independent\nAustria\u201d has no voice in the control of the river that\ntraverses her whole length and the price for getting it\nis apparently to join the Soviet bloc.\nWe are slipping in Europe, despite the far greater\nprosperity of the west compared with the east, and de\nspite the utter failure of Communism, as spontaneous\nrevolutionary movement. A redressing of the situation\nis not to be found in Moscow. The Russian leadership is\nimpelled toward advancement, first by fundamental\ntheory, and second by Russian necessity.\nThe war revealed to the Russian leadership, if not to\nourselves, prodigious weaknesses in the Soviet system.\nRussia needs western brains, technics, organization\nand experience. To get these by opening her frontiers\nwould threaten the Communist dictatorship. She must\nget them on her own terms, and now, as in Lenin\u2019s time,\nthe hope is from Germany, the country and people that\nRussia, whatever her hates, has always most admired.\nTo think that Russia will voluntarily retreat an inch\nfrom Germany or \u201cco-operate\u201d in any program aimed\nat keeping Germany out of the Russian orbit is to cher\nish a hopeless illusion.\nHope does not, therefore lie in Moscow. Nor in Frank\nfort and the new west-German government. It lies in\nLondon, Paris and Washington, and in the possibility of\ncreating a genuine western union, a real United States\nof what still remains of Europe, with rump Germany in\nit as an equal. Unless there is war, eastern Germany is\ngone, for the time being, as a European civilization, and\nby \u201ctime being\u201d I mean the lifetime of the Soviet Union,\nwhatever it may be. But it will be longer than the life\ntime of Europe if Britain, above all, France, persist in\nj half-measures and continue to be ruled by old fears\nj whose entire basis has disappeared.\nMany Names\nSuggested For\nReceding Glaciei\n(By Vern Haugland)\nM/P) Special Washington Ser\nWASHINGTON, (/P)\u2014An\ncreated by the gradual meltin\nan Alaskan glacier may be na\nfor the University of Wisconsi\nIt is one of 32 places in gk\nbay national monument, so\neastern Alaska, under study\nthe U. S. board on geogra\nnames.\nThe national park service\npreparing a new map of the a\nand has asked the board to dc\nnate officially the names for v\nous features, including those\nated by the year-to-year re\nsion of the glaciers.\nMany of the names propi\nare connected with early exp\ntions into Alaska.\nThe feature which has t\nshown on some maps as Cusl\nInlet would be named Wiscoi\nInlet, in one proposal before\nboard, because of the many i\nversity scientists who have st\nied the glacier bay area. The\nlet was formed in recent years\nthe recession of Plauteau glac\nMuir glacier, one of Alasl\ngreatest glacial bodies, 1\nnamed for naturalist John Mui\nWisconsin alumnus.\nOther proposed names now\nfore the board for the glacier 1\nmonument area, include:\nFlapjack island. It\u2019s in an a\nof sfrallow water \u201cand as the t\nfalls the portion about water\npears to spread out like thin t\nter on a griddle.\u201d\nBurroughs glacier, west of M\ninlet\u2014for John Burroughs, v\nvisited the inlet with the Hai\nman expedition in 1899.\n\nHunter cove, west side of M\ninlet\u2014for Captain Hunter of\nS. S. City of Topeka, which v\nited the inlet in 1892.\nJohnson Cove, northeast sh<\nof Willoughby Island\u2014for Jo\nJohnson, a fox farmer.\nGeorge point, southwes t e\nend of Strawberry island\u2014for\nE. George, pilot of the S. S. Id\u00ab\nwhich visited .glacier bay in 18\nElder point, northern point\nthe Beardslee islands\u2014for the\nS. George W. Elder, which visi\nGlacier bay in 1892 and was us\nby the Harriman expedition\n1899.\nMartin islands, in the easte\npart of Glacier bay\u2014E. R. Marti\na member of the internation\nboundary commission\u2019s 1907\nvey party.\nSpokane cove, east shore of gl\ncier Bay\u2014the S. S. Spokane, oi\nof the Alaskan exploratory ve\nsels.\nTidal inlet, on Glacier Bay o\nposite Gilbert island\u2014Reid\u2019s e:\npedition in 1890 made tidal o'\nservations there.\nPoint Wachusett, west side\nMuir inlet\u2014the U. S. sloop\nwar Wachusett which visited tl\narea in 1881.\nYork river, four miles Ion\nempties into glacier bay opposi\nSouth Marble island Willia\nYork, a camp helper with Reic\n1892 expedition.\nYoung island, in the Beards!\ngroup\u2014the Rev. Samuel H;\nYoung, who accompanied Muir\nthe area in 1879-89.\nOther names proposed: Anchc\nage cove, since 1931 the best a\nchorage in the area; Beartra","height":"28252","width":"18984"}}
